turns.userMessage: Search latest news about US tariff rate against China/Japan/EU
turns.assistantText:
Here's the latest news on US tariff rates (as of January 2026):

### China
- **Current rate:** 20% (10% reciprocal + 10% fentanyl tariffs)
- **Future rate:** Set to increase to 44% on November 10, 2026
- Section 301 tariffs (~25-30%) apply to many products
- China faces the highest tariff rates among major trading partners

### Japan
- **Current rate:** 15% on auto imports (effective September 16, 2025)
- EU and Japan tariffs are combined and capped at 15% for certain products like furniture

### European Union
- **Current rate:** 15% cap on certain products (like furniture)
- **New tariff threat:** Trump announced 8 NATO allies (including EU members) would face 10% tariffs next month, rising to 25% by June unless a deal is reached for the "Complete and Total purchase of Greenland"
- The EU is discussing approximately $108 billion in retaliatory tariffs

### General Policy
The Trump administration has implemented a minimum 10% baseline tariff on all trading partners, with specific countries facing higher rates based on reciprocal tariffs and other factors.

Sources:
- [Trump Tariffs: The Economic Impact of the Trump Trade War](https://taxfoundation.org/research/all/federal/trump-tariffs-trade-war/)
- [Trump 2.0 tariff tracker](https://www.tradecomplianceresourcehub.com/2026/01/14/trump-2-0-tariff-tracker/)
- [Tariffs in 2026: How new trade rules impact your business](https://www.avalara.com/blog/en/north-america/2026/01/tariffs-2026-how-new-trade-rules-impact-business.html)
- [Just when Wall Street and Corporate America were looking forward to a year without trade fears](https://fortune.com/2026/01/17/trump-trade-war-nato-tariff-iran-duty-china-eu-deal-inflation-gdp-growth/)
- [Trump tariffs live updates](https://finance.yahoo.com/news/live/trump-tariffs-live-updates-trump-announces-tariffs-on-european-countries-until-deal-is-reached-for-purchase-of-greenland-152657152.html)

turns.userMessage: Write a python code to convert them to a simple html chart
turns.assistantText:
Perfect! I've created and executed a Python script that converts the CSV tariff data to an HTML chart. Here's what the script does:

**Features:**
- **Bar Chart:** Visualizes current vs. future tariff rates side-by-side using Chart.js
- **Data Table:** Displays all tariff information in an organized table format
- **Responsive Design:** The chart adjusts to different screen sizes
- **Color Coding:** 
  - Blue bars for current rates
  - Orange bars for future rates
  - Highlighted table columns for easy reading

**Generated Files:**
1. `csv_to_html_chart.py` - The Python script
2. `us_tariffs_chart.html` - The output HTML file

You can open `us_tariffs_chart.html` in any web browser to view the interactive chart and table with all the US tariff information for China, Japan, and the EU.
